00:08.880 --> 00:12.880
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:30.000 --> 00:35.020
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:37.760 --> 00:39.420
And here are your hosts.

00:44.760 --> 00:54.780
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. Philip Jose Farmer has been a mainstay
science fiction writer since 1952. He has written over 40 novels and over 80

00:54.780 --> 01:04.960
short stories focusing on a wide variety of subjects. These range from Tarzan to
the afterlife, from sex-crazed aliens to a star-faring Catholic priest. Farmer's

01:04.960 --> 01:13.960
most famous works are the Riverworld series, the World of Tears series, his
erotic fantasy novels, and the story, later a novel, The Lovers. We asked Farmer

01:13.960 --> 01:26.760
how he started writing science fiction. I started reading science fiction when I
was seven years old. I'm 63 now, and I knew I always wanted to be a writer.

01:27.600 --> 01:38.480
Although I didn't do much about it for many years. The funny thing is, I
actually intended to become a mainstream writer. That is, to write stories which

01:38.480 --> 01:50.840
are not in a particular genre. But I somehow or other just drifted into science
fiction. And sold my first science fiction story in 1952. That was called The

01:50.840 --> 02:03.760
Lovers. It was a novelette, which was published in a magazine. And it's
generally credited with breaking the taboo against the mature use of sex in a

02:03.760 --> 02:16.000
science fiction magazine. We asked Farmer if he consciously set out to break
taboos by writing The Lovers. No, I had an idea for a story, and I couldn't

02:16.000 --> 02:25.660
write it unless I broke the taboos. I didn't really consciously set out to do
it, because I had the idea, and I thought it was terrific. On the other hand, I

02:25.660 --> 02:37.140
knew I was going to have a lot of trouble getting it accepted. I did. Did have a
lot of trouble. The first editor I sent it to, John Campbell, who was the editor

02:37.140 --> 02:50.120
of Astounding, was the most prestigious and highest paying market. So naturally,
I sent it to him first. And he returned it with a comment that nauseated him. So

02:50.120 --> 03:01.380
I sent it to Horace Gold, who was editing Galaxy, which was equally prestigious
and had about the same word rate. His comments were something like John

03:01.380 --> 03:15.400
Campbell's. So then I sent it to Samuel Mines, who was editor of a magazine
called Startling Stories. And he immediately accepted it and knew it was a

03:15.400 --> 03:29.100
revolutionary breakthrough. I published it, and I was on my way. Except that the
next story I wrote was also equally revolutionary, and it took me a year before

03:29.100 --> 03:41.080
I could get anybody to accept it. Farmer is also interested in religion in its
varied forms, and has used it in his works. My interest in religion has

03:41.080 --> 03:52.100
manifested itself throughout all my works. Although a lot of people, when they
say the name Farmer, immediately think of sex in the book. But the fact is I've

03:52.100 --> 04:08.380
written much more about religion than about sex. Or sometimes both at the same
time. But in some respects, sex and religion are two sides of the same coin. In

04:08.380 --> 04:10.200
certain fields of activity.

04:15.760 --> 04:24.200
But religion is only one of many themes. Farmer feels that he may have labored
in relative anonymity for years because his writings are so varied. But he has

04:24.200 --> 04:36.520
his reasons. One of the reasons I've had trouble in the early days, I think,
really becoming identified and getting a band of followers, is that I didn't

04:36.520 --> 04:50.800
beat on just one or two drums. I ranged all over the field. But I find out that
if I do a variety of stuff, I don't get tired. Each new novel is a new

04:50.800 --> 04:57.560
challenge. I'm not just working the same old theme again. Tomorrow we continue
with more on Philip Jose Farmer.

05:05.000 --> 05:12.980
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:12.980 --> 05:13.740
Odessa, Texas.

05:57.580 --> 06:01.660
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:16.840 --> 06:22.120
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:24.920 --> 06:26.540
And here are your hosts.

06:31.260 --> 06:39.420
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. We're continuing our interview with Philip
Jose Farmer. We want to explore here some background related to one of

06:39.420 --> 06:48.480
Farmer's major themes, religion. As Farmer allowed earlier, he considers himself
a writer of religious themes, even more so than a writer of sexual themes. His

06:48.480 --> 06:57.360
own religious background is quite checkered. I was sent to Sunday school when I
was very little, and I became interested in the Bible, and I read it on my own.

06:57.960 --> 07:10.700
And I even read the Book of Mormon when I was about nine years old. And I always
wrestled all my life with the problems of immortality, predestination, grace,

07:11.820 --> 07:25.920
the afterlife, and all that sort of stuff. I was raised as a Christian scientist
up until the time I was about 12. And then I was sent to a Presbyterian church

07:25.920 --> 07:29.180
where

07:29.180 --> 07:41.400
there was a conflict between Christian science and the Presbyterian idea of
predestination. And then when I was about 16, I guess I became an atheist. I've

07:41.400 --> 07:56.540
gone through atheism through agnosticism, and then I was converted to the
disciples of Christ. And then I backslid myself from grace, as the theological

07:56.540 --> 08:09.880
term goes. And then I lapsed back into agnosticism. And what are Farmer's
present beliefs? My present situation is that without immortality, life has no

08:09.880 --> 08:23.040
meaning. And if there's a creation, there must be a creator. But I've become
tremendously interested in what is sometimes referred to as mythicism. It isn't

08:23.040 --> 08:42.680
really like the Muslim Sufism. It's cool. Then a lot of related stuff like that.
You might say right now I'm in sort of a limbo. Heading toward something, I

08:42.680 --> 08:51.440
don't know what. The concept of an afterlife appears repeatedly in Farmer's
works. Well, if you think about it, there could be a million different

08:51.440 --> 09:08.720
possibilities in an afterlife if there were work. But one of my perhaps unstated
themes is that immortality may not depend upon a supernatural being. That it's

09:08.720 --> 09:14.420
in the evolutionary drive of man for him to invent immortality himself.

09:17.020 --> 09:26.500
The drawback to that is that those people who are already dead will remain dead,
right? So that doesn't correspond to the religious idea of immortality, where

09:26.500 --> 09:41.420
everybody is raised. From the first human being to the last one. I like to do a
lot of variations on that. I have a new book called The Unreasoning Mask. That's

09:41.420 --> 09:56.380
a quotation from Moby Dick. And this is concerned with theology, afterlife,
immortality. You might call it a philosophical-theological space opera.

10:12.800 --> 10:22.000
Many of Farmer's first works had the central theme of religion. The Lovers and A
Woman a Day deal with a future amalgamation of church and state called the

10:22.000 --> 10:30.560
Sturch. A popular character, Father John Carmody, is a planet-hopping Catholic
priest who has appeared in several short stories. We learn about his former life

10:30.560 --> 10:39.800
and conversion in the excellent novel, Night of Light. Inside Outside is a wild
tale about the afterlife and immortality. It is in fact the predecessor to the

10:39.800 --> 10:43.340
famous Riverworld series, which we will discuss in our next show.

10:50.580 --> 10:58.520
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:58.520 --> 10:59.280
Odessa, Texas.

11:44.640 --> 11:48.540
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:04.000 --> 12:09.380
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:12.040 --> 12:13.760
And here are your hosts.

12:18.300 --> 12:27.100
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. Having looked into Philip Jose Farmer's
feelings on religion and immortality, we began a look today at the Riverworld

12:27.100 --> 12:41.080
series. Farmer explains the basis of the story. It concerns the planet in which
there is a 10 million mile long river, which follows the valley. And everybody

12:41.080 --> 12:55.100
that lived from about 150,000 B.C. to about 1983 A.D. was resurrected along the
banks of the river in rejuvenated form. It looks like there were 25. And the

12:55.100 --> 13:02.000
main mystery behind the whole thing was, why were all these people resurrected?

13:04.100 --> 13:14.880
Who did it and how? But the Riverworld concept is so big that Farmer has
managed only to scratch the surface in the four main novels of the series. There

13:14.880 --> 13:25.120
are so many themes that I wanted to explore during the course of those four
novels, but I couldn't do it because I would have slowed the story down too

13:25.120 --> 13:35.860
much. It would have taken too many sidetracks, you might say, and I'd still be
working on that particular series. What else is left? Listen to Farmer as he

13:35.860 --> 13:45.820
gives us an inkling of what he would like to cover. I didn't go into any detail
in how you could work out viable societies with people from every place and

13:45.820 --> 14:03.680
every time. I also wanted to bring up in depth what would happen to famous
people on that planet. Like, well, there's Karl Marx, for instance. What would

14:03.680 --> 14:17.960
he think of what happened to his ideas about communism on the planet Earth after
he died? Leonardo da Vinci, his ideas about art, plus the fact that he's on a

14:17.960 --> 14:25.160
planet where there are very few pigments available, for instance, for him to
paint. What would he do there?

14:28.160 --> 14:32.840
I also wanted to bring

14:32.840 --> 14:42.360
up various figures from science and the military and philosophy and so forth to
show what they would do there. Now, one of the things about the river world was

14:42.360 --> 14:57.460
that although you were resurrected there in a youthful body of your own, as it
was at 25 or earlier, if you died before 25, if, for instance, you were 83 when

14:57.460 --> 15:11.740
you died, and your mind is still 83 and you have 83 years of experience on Earth
behind you, now, is your character formed? Are you going to go through perhaps a

15:11.740 --> 15:21.900
thousand years being the same person? Or are you going to improve? And is the
magic labyrinth the last word on the river world? I made a lot of people mad at

15:21.900 --> 15:34.320
me. Because of that last sentence there, your paragraph, I should say, that I
wrote in the magic labyrinth, everything seems to have been settled. Everything

15:34.320 --> 15:48.760
has been cleared up. And then one of the characters, the kind of minor one,
Peter Jairus Frigate, he's celebrating with the others in the misty tar, when

15:48.760 --> 15:59.440
he thinks he hears a football outside in the hallway. Close out, comes back, and
says to the others, I didn't see anyone. It must have been my imagination. A lot

15:59.440 --> 16:07.460
of readers got mad at me because they thought, oh no, he's going to write
another one. He's leaving a loophole. Well, I am leaving a loophole. And I don't

16:07.460 --> 16:20.220
know whether I'll go through it or not. But it's quite possible that the magic
labyrinth wasn't the final one in that series before. Everything that our

16:20.220 --> 16:31.300
protagonist learned, and everything that everybody else learned, is completely
untrue or has to true. So the Riverworld novels may or may not be finished, but

16:31.300 --> 16:35.420
we do have some more sidestream stories to anticipate. More on Farmer tomorrow.

16:42.880 --> 16:50.800
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:50.800 --> 16:51.580
Odessa, Texas.

17:37.420 --> 17:43.520
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

17:56.920 --> 18:02.300
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
