18:04.980 --> 18:06.720
And here are your hosts.

18:10.480 --> 18:20.180
This is Bill Vernon. And David Crews. Our show today continues the
discussion with Philip Jose Farmer. A major incident in Farmer's career began

18:20.180 --> 18:29.300
when Venus on the Half Shell, a novel written under the pseudonym Kilgore Trout,
appeared in the pages of fantasy and science fiction in late 74, early 75. Of

18:29.300 --> 18:37.120
course, Kilgore Trout is the creation of author Kurt Vonnegut, Jr. The character
Trout is an impoverished, underappreciated science fiction writer who appears in

18:37.120 --> 18:47.280
a number of Vonnegut's novels. We asked Farmer if he identifies with Kilgore
Trout. I was a fan of Vonnegut. I liked all his books, but Kilgore Trout really

18:47.280 --> 18:59.940
turned me on because his early experiences, as a matter of fact his later ones
too, were like a lot of my early experiences, and a lot like the experiences of

18:59.940 --> 19:10.160
many other science fiction writers. Back in the old days when they weren't being
paid much, and science fiction was looked down upon, and we were being taken due

19:10.160 --> 19:23.140
to our inexperience by various publishers and agents. Also, I had a tough time
getting any recognition. So, I guess that's why I identified with him. Plus the

19:23.140 --> 19:32.340
fact he's a great character. Vonnegut did not appreciate the reviews given Venus
on the Half Shell, either pro or con, because most of the reviewers approached

19:32.340 --> 19:41.520
the work as if Vonnegut were the author. This cost Farmer the opportunity to
write another novel under the Kilgore Trout pseudonym. I don't know what his

19:41.520 --> 19:53.260
reactions are to the novel itself, but so many people thought that he'd written
it, that he was deluded, hundreds of maybe thousands of questions, and then the

19:53.260 --> 20:02.480
reviews came out. Some said Venus on the Half Shell by Kilgore Trout. Well, it
was the worst thing he'd written, and others said it was the best thing he'd

20:02.480 --> 20:11.220
ever written. So, when I applied for permission to write The Son of Jimmy
Valentine, which I really would have loved to have done, because I could have

20:11.220 --> 20:26.380
had a lot of fun with it, he said no, which is his prerogative. We asked if The
Son of Jimmy Valentine was Kilgore Trout's one erotic novel. It was not only his

20:26.380 --> 20:36.800
one and only specifically erotic book, it was also his only non-science fiction
book. Farmer obviously enjoys writing about fictional authors, who in turn write

20:36.800 --> 20:47.540
about their own fictional authors, and so on. Listen as he describes what
writing as Kilgore Trout started. In The Venus on the Half Shell, the

20:47.540 --> 20:59.600
protagonist, Simon Wagstaff, had his favorite science fiction author. Just as in
the Vonnegut books, Eliot Rosewater thought that Kilgore Trout was the greatest

20:59.600 --> 21:07.740
living writer in any field. He should have been president of the U.S. He
couldn't solve all the problems. Well, anyway, in The Venus on the Half Shell,

21:09.120 --> 21:21.300
Simon Wagstaff liked to read the science fiction works of a fellow called
Jonathan Swift Somers III. And I described his various works, or outline them,

21:21.460 --> 21:35.680
as a title. But Jonathan Swift Somers, who's a fiction author, wrote about a
giant German Shepherd police dog whose IQ had been raised to about 200 in a

21:35.680 --> 21:49.360
laboratory, and he became a private detective. Now, I plan eventually someday on
writing a book by Ralph von Valvao, the dog, under the name of Ralph von Valvao.

21:50.700 --> 22:02.580
And then maybe I'll end the cycle by having Ralph von Valvao write about a human
named Vonnegut, something like that, and completing it, going right back to

22:02.580 --> 22:10.900
Vonnegut again. Farmer conceived of the extended family group called the Wold
-Newton family, in which many great historical and fictional characters are

22:10.900 --> 22:20.400
descended from the Scarlet Pimpernel. Thus, Kilgore Trout is related to Sherlock
Holmes, Doc Savage, Sam Spade, and James Bond, among others. We will look into

22:20.400 --> 22:22.800
this aspect of Farmer's writing some more tomorrow.

22:30.200 --> 22:38.180
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

22:38.180 --> 22:38.940
Odessa, Texas.

23:25.700 --> 23:29.620
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:45.100 --> 23:50.500
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

23:53.180 --> 23:54.880
And here are your hosts.

23:59.520 --> 24:08.440
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. This show will conclude our interview with
Philip Jose Farmer. Yesterday, we discussed Farmer's penchant for writing under

24:08.440 --> 24:12.480
pseudonyms. As it turns out, this practice has a very desirable side effect.

24:35.560 --> 24:45.500
But when they sit down in front of the typewriter, nothing happened. Well, that
happened to me once. I never thought it would. I thought I was immune to such a

24:45.500 --> 25:00.160
thing. But it did. And after wrestling for two months and getting no place, I
had an idea. I sat down with the typewriter and wrote a story, not by Philip

25:00.160 --> 25:16.840
Jose Farmer, but by David Copperfield, they say. I don't remember which
particular nominacy. The story poured out. Very good. I thought so, anyway. When

25:16.840 --> 25:29.000
I completed that, the writing block was gone. See, I wasn't writing then as me,
so both a Farmer, but as a Kilgore Trout. And I was in his shoes. I had no

25:29.000 --> 25:44.700
trouble. Now, the funny thing about this is that the, uh, it's a psychological
trick that I'm conscious of, see. And yet it works. It's not like I'm trying to

25:44.700 --> 25:56.000
trick my unconscious, but I must be doing it one way or another. Well, I don't
know if anybody else has ever broken the writer's block in that manner. But I

25:56.000 --> 26:07.380
recommend trying it. Farmer has also written several books featuring Tarzan or
Tarzan-like characters. Tarzan Alive is Tarzan's biography. The erotic novel A

26:07.380 --> 26:18.080
Feast Unknown and its clean sequels The Mad Goblin and Lord of the Trees feature
thinly veiled versions of Tarzan and Doc Savage. Lord Tiger, the Opar books, and

26:18.080 --> 26:27.480
The Adventures of the Peerless Peer also have Tarzan-like protagonists. We asked
Farmer when he developed his interest in Tarzan. I first read Tarzan when I

26:27.480 --> 26:35.920
guess I was about seven or eight years old, and I became wrapped up in that
early age with the works of Edgar Rice Burroughs.

26:38.600 --> 26:43.920
And, but when I started college, I kind of lost interest and didn't read them
anymore.

26:49.700 --> 26:59.880
But later, Farmer picked up on Tarzan again. This time, he saw Tarzan in a
different light. I started reading books about Tarzan again, and this time,

27:00.740 --> 27:14.620
although I still kept a lot of my childhood interest in him, a sense of wonder
about him, I began seeing things in Tarzan, for instance, that I had not seen

27:14.620 --> 27:28.280
before. Tarzan was not just a child who'd been cast away and raised by great
apes and then become a creature of the jungle, then returned to claim fortune.

27:28.280 --> 27:42.700
And he was sort of an archetype of many, many heroes from classical myths. And
now, I'm sure that when Burroughs wrote this, he didn't know what he was doing,

27:42.760 --> 27:52.680
but he did it unconsciously. I think that the creation of Tarzan is a stroke of
genius. Burroughs is not a great writer, but he has created a great character,

27:52.760 --> 28:03.860
just like Acorn and Doyle is not a great writer, but he created a great
character. Sherlock Holmes. Philip Jose Farmer. An author with a seemingly

28:03.860 --> 28:08.980
endless supply of unique ideas, who appears just now to be gaining widespread
acceptance.

28:16.580 --> 28:24.520
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

28:24.520 --> 28:42.960
Odessa, Texas. 

